                                <condition>
                                    <p>
                                        <q>'Poor; the ogham, which is worn and in a bad condition, is defaced by series of spalls on the arris'</q> (Forsyth 1996, 290). There is general weathering with large spaced chunks missing from the arris. <q>'The stone has fallen and been re-erected at least twice'</q>, the first time it was toppled by some young men while the second was natural due to the damage caused at the base during its first fall (Forsyth 1996, 288-289).
                                    </p>
                                </condition>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout>
                                    <p>
                                        <q>It is unclear whether the monument is a re-used pre-historic standing stone or a pillar specially erected for the bearing of the inscription'</q> (Forsyth 1996,289). It used to be part of an alignment of three stones, located in the middle. The stone is located to the north-east on a hillock where further up there was an upright cross which broke and fell around 1793.
                                    </p>
                                </layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote>
                                <p>
                                   There is a wide range of published interpertation that along with its general poor condition make a definitive reading difficult. On the same grounds, it is difficult to make definitive statements about its carving technique.<q>'As they now survive, the strokes are finger-scale and with a U-section. Where it can be measured with any certainty the length of h-aicme strokes is about <height unit="cm">6</height></q> (Forsyth 1996, 291). The gaps in between the inscriptions most likely contain vowel notches now lost. 
                                </p>
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
